<p style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px;">The Benefits of Senior Living</p>

<!-- Paragraph 1 of text -->
<p style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px;">It's easy to make new friends. When you reach a certain age, making new friends can be a struggle because you can't rely on school or work to meet people who are similar to you. At a retirement community, however, you immediately become a part of a welcoming community of seniors. You're bound to make some great new friends among the residents (as well as the staff).</p>

<!-- Paragraph 2 of text -->
<p style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px;">There are a variety of activities and social events. Residents of a retirement community have so many great opportunities at their doorstep: exercise classes, visiting entertainers, group outings, movie nights, games, clubs for all sorts of hobbies . . . If you're bored, you have no one to blame but yourself.</p>

<!-- Paragraph 3 of text -->
<p style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px;">No cooking, housework, or property upkeep required. Homeownership comes with so many taxing chores: mowing the lawn, cleaning the bathroom, shoveling snow, etc. One of the most delightful benefits of living in a retirement community is that you won't have to worry about these tasks anymore. You won???t even have to cook your own meals!</p>

<!-- Paragraph 4 of text -->
<p style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px;">Medical services are offered. Living alone in your later years can be stressful, especially if you have pressing health concerns. The emergency response systems and reliable staff members will help you feel safe and secure. You'll cherish the peace of mind you have after moving into your new home.</p>
